abstract = {An aspect of anthropogenic impacts on climate have been assessed by examining the day-of-the-week variation (DOWV) of important meteorological elements. The data used were those of daily maximum and minimum temperature and rainfall for Melbourne for the period 1856{\^{a}}1990. This long series has been broken up into five 27-yr subperiods to expose how any such variation has changed over the record. We find there to be no DOWV in the summer {\^{a}}half{\^{a}} of the year for any of the subperiods. The only statistically significant variations to have physical meaning occur in the winter of the most recent subperiod (1964{\^{a}}1990). In that time maximum temperature exhibits a significant (10{\%} confidence level) DOWV and weekdays are 0.29{\^{A}}°C warmer than weekends (5{\%}). Minimum temperatures and rainfall amounts were also found to be greater (10{\%} level) on weekdays by 0.24{\^{A}}°C and 0.20 mm d{\^{a}}1, respectively.

